fore it (**if it exists**) has a height **strictly greater** than `threshold`. **Note** that mountain 0 is **not** stable.\n\nReturn an array containing the indices of *all* **stable** mountains in **any** order.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** height = [1,2,3,4,5], threshold = 2\n\n**Output:** [3,4]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\n- Mountain 3 is stable because `height[2] == 3` is greater than `threshold == 2`.\n\n- Mountain 4 is stable because `height[3] == 4` is greater than `threshold == 2`.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** height = [10,1,10,1,10], threshold = 3\n\n**Output:** [1,3]\n\n**Example 3:**\n\n**Input:** height = [10,1,10,1,10], threshold = 10\n\n**Output:** []\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= n == height.length <= 100`\n\n- `1 <= height[i] <= 100`\n\n- `1 <= threshold <= 100`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"There are `n` mountains in a row, and each mountain has a height. You are given an integer array `height` where `height[i]` represents the height of mountain `i`, and an integer `threshold`.\n\nA mountain is called **stable** if the mountain just before it (**if it exists**) has a height **strictly greater** than `threshold`. **Note** that mountain 0 is **not** stable.\n\nReturn an array containing the indices of *all* **stable** mountains in **any** order.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** height = [1,2,3,4,5], threshold = 2\n\n**Output:** [3,4]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\n- Mountain 3 is stable because `height[2] == 3` is greater than `threshold == 2`.\n\n- Mountain 4 is stable because `height[3] == 4` is greater than `threshold == 2`.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** height = [10,1,10,1,10], threshold = 3\n\n**Output:** [1,3]\n\n**Example 3:**\n\n**Input:** height = [10,1,10,1,10], threshold = 10\n\n**Output:** []\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= n == height.length <= 100`\n\n- `1 <= height[i] <= 100`\n\n- `1 <= threshold <= 100`","problemLi